{{unreferenced|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox news event | title = Sinking of the steamer Mayakovsky | image = | caption = | date = 13 August 1950 | time = | place = Daugava | coordinates = | also known as = | cause = Vessel overloaded | participants = | outcome = {{plainlist | * 147 deaths * }} | reported injuries = | reported death(s) = | reported missing = | reported property damage = | burial = | enquiries = | inquest = | coroner = | suspects = | charges = | verdict = | convictions = | publication bans = | litigation = | awards = | url = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }}
On August 13, 1950, the steamer '''''Mayakovsky''''' (named for Soviet poet [[Vladimir Mayakovsky]]) sank at around 12:00 pm local time due to overloading of the vessel with too many people. ''Mayakovsky'' sank in the [[Daugava]] River that bisects [[Riga]], not more than {{convert|15|m}} from the present day site of the [[Stone Bridge, Riga|Stone Bridge]]. A total of 147 people died, including 48 children. It was the deadliest peacetime disaster in Soviet Latvian history. At the time, Latvia was a republic within the Soviet Union, under the rule of Joseph Stalin, and news of the disaster was not put in the state-controlled press. On August 19, 2011, almost 20 years after the breakup of the Soviet Union and the Republic of Latvia regaining its independence, a memorial plaque was dedicated at the Stone Bridge (the ''Akmens tilts'') in memory of the victims. <ref>[http://www.delfi.lv/reporter/news/witness/na-naberezhnoj-otkryt-memorial-v-pamyat-o-pogibshih-na-parohode-mayakovskij.d?id=40204997 "On the embankment a memorial was opened in memory of those who died on the steamer 'Mayakovsky'"] (Article on Delfi, August 20, 2011, about the erection of a memorial plaque)</ref>
