{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}
The '''National Union for Democracy and Progress''' ({{lang-pt|União Nacional para a Democracia e o Progresso}}, UNDP) is a [[political party]] in [[Guinea-Bissau]].
==History== The party was established on 5 December 1997 by [[Abubácar Baldé]].<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p403</ref> In the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1999–2000|1999 general elections]] Baldé finished sixth in the presidential elections with 5% of the vote, whilst the party won a single seat in the [[National People's Assembly (Guinea-Bissau)|National People's Assembly]] with just under 1% of the vote.
Despite a slight increase of its vote share to 1.2% in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]], the party lost its only seat in the Assembly. Baldé pulled out of the [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2005|2005 presidential elections]] two weeks before election day, claiming the election was "infected with vices" that undermined the "political and juridical guarantees of liberty, transparency and justice."<ref name=HD/>
The party failed to win a seat in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 parliamentary elections]], receiving just 0.3% of the vote. It did not contest the [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2009|2009]] or [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2012|2012 presidential elections]], but supported the [[2012 Guinea-Bissau coup d'état|2012 military coup]].<ref name=HD/>
